                    <span>... This is not an in-depth study of the racism/speciesim connection. It is, however, a thought-provoking introduction to the topic. The way in which societies foster master classes is a timely subject, particularly in the fact of the new wave of burgeoning imperialism known as globalism. I expect this issue to attract much interest in the near future. It will be a turning point for all social justice movements when we see and acknowledge the interconnected nature of oppression.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Wonderful! Challenging! Interrogates assumptions!</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>0</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2001-01-24</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>This amazing book is important not only because it examines the thought-processes of the paradigmatic Western culture of violence, but because it gives a voice to the voiceless: animals. While patriarchy continues to rape and dismember the ecologies of "third world" nations, animal slavery is alive and well in the white "civilized" western nations. Why is this? This terrific book will help all empathic peoples to challenge accepted ideologies of oppression and degradation. But perhaps this book is too brilliantly insightful, too challenging of some people's most closely-held assumptions, too much an indictment of white male patriarchy, to be found acceptable outside of academe. That would be a shame, but because progressive thought is now almost exclusively found on college campuses (where animal testing has often been successfully protested against), the dominant culture will try to ignore this book. As Alice Walker points out, however, this book "will take a lifetime to forget."</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">A must read for anyone interested in the subject</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
